ck-on-wordcamp-boston-2016/">Read More</a></p>
<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/webpro/wordpress/looking-back-on-wordcamp-boston-2016/">Looking back on WordCamp Boston 2016</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage">Garage</a>.</p>
";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:9:"enclosure";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:3:{s:3:"url";s:90:"https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/wordcamp-boston-2016-305x170.jpg";s:6:"length";s:1:"0";s:4:"type";s:10:"image/jpeg";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:13:"Andy McIlwain";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:10981:"<p>Prior to <a href="https://2016.boston.wordcamp.org/" target="_blank">WordCamp Boston 2016</a>, my only knowledge of the city came from <a href="http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0402711/" target="_blank">‚ÄúBoston Legal.‚Äù</a>¬†And as much as I loved those heartfelt bonding moments between James Spader and William Shatner on the balcony, they didn‚Äôt do much to familiarize me with the city of Boston proper. (Alas.)</p>
<p>Thankfully, the <a href="https://2016.boston.wordcamp.org/organizers/" target="_blank">WordCamp Boston organizers</a>¬†did a much better job of introducing their hometown to a naive visitor like myself.</p>
<p><a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/wordcamp-boston-2016-boston-university.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-16385" src="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/wordcamp-boston-2016-boston-university.jpg" alt="WordCamp Boston 2016 Boston University" width="640" height="480" srcset="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/wordcamp-boston-2016-boston-university.jpg 640w, https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/wordcamp-boston-2016-boston-university-768x576.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400;">WordCamp Boston 2016: Stories and serendipity</span></h2>
<p><a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/wordcamp-boston-2016-view.jpg"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-16383" src="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/wordcamp-boston-2016-view.jpg" alt="WordCamp Boston 2016 View" width="400" height="300" srcset="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/wordcamp-boston-2016-view.jpg 400w, https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/wordcamp-boston-2016-view-768x576.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 400px) 100vw, 400px" /></a></p>
<p>Boston University was a perfect venue in a perfect location. Perched on the shore of the Charles River, it offered a direct view of kayakers and boaters floating along in picturesque weather. (Not that we were envious or anything.)</p>
<p>Attendee check-in was effortless (props to <a href="https://twitter.com/jeckman" target="_blank">John Eckman</a>¬†and Co. for rocking the registration desk), and the common space ‚Äî wrapped by sponsors and filled with seating ‚Äî encouraged mingling and conversation.</p>
<p>We saw more of that mingling during lunch, with attendees grabbing bagged meals and taking a seat at shared tables. And we saw it again at the after party, where there was enough seating for people to gather and chat over food and drink.</p>
<blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-lang="en">
<p dir="ltr" lang="en">Lunch break at <a href="https://twitter.com/WordCampBoston">@WordCampBoston</a> . Beautifully organised! <a href="https://twitter.com/hashtag/wcbos?src=hash">#wcbos</a> <a href="https://t.co/cgqatrvf5h">pic.twitter.com/cgqatrvf5h</a></p>
<p>‚Äî PressTigers (@press_tigers) <a href="https://twitter.com/press_tigers/status/756890616538292224">July 23, 2016</a></p></blockquote>
<p><script src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" async="" charset="utf-8"></script></p>
<p>Now, I don‚Äôt know if this was intentional or not. Maybe the layout and seating, and the conversations and sharing they facilitated, was entirely serendipitous. It‚Äôs hard to say. But I do know that I walked away from WordCamp Boston with one word stuck in my head:</p>
<p><em>Stories.</em></p>
<p>We all have them. And for many of us ‚Äî certainly those who are attending an event like #WCBOS ‚Äî WordPress plays a key role in how our stories get shared.</p>
<h2>WordCamps are great for sharing stories.</h2>
<p>You meet people face-to-face, ask them questions, answer theirs, and learn how they‚Äôre using WordPress. We met artists in need of an online portfolio, crafters and makers looking to sell products to faraway customers, and writers who just wanted to share their work. They were moonlighters, retired, hobbyists, professionals and fresh college graduates (not surprising, considering we were in Boston).</p>
<p>There are a lot of places to hear stories at a WordCamp. They‚Äôre often the basis of <a href="http://chrislema.com/delivering-great-technology-presentations/" target="_blank">great presentations</a>. But I‚Äôd argue that the single best place to hear stories is in the <a href="http://sachachua.com/blog/2010/12/making-the-most-of-the-conference-hallway-track/" target="_blank">hallway track</a>.</p>
<div class="callout"> Take the hallway track. It rocks. </div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>And if you‚Äôve never heard of the hallway track you‚Äôre probably asking yourself, ‚Äúwhat the heck is a hallway track?‚Äù</p>
<p>The idea is simple: Instead of sitting in on sessions, you spend your time sitting in common spaces ‚Äî like hallways, hence the name ‚Äî chatting with other attendees. You can chat about whatever you want, WordPress or otherwise, and you‚Äôll likely walk away with stronger connections than if you just sat in sessions.</p>
<p>Some say that hallway tracks are the best part of a WordCamp. (Just don‚Äôt try to find it on the schedule.)</p>
<h2>Booths are boring.</h2>
<p>The sponsor experience typically involves sitting behind a swag-covered table. There‚Äôs nothing wrong with that. It‚Äôs just a bit boring. So we tried something different this time, choosing instead to create a space that encourages the aforementioned hallway track moments.</p>
<div id="attachment_16384" style="width: 650px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/godaddy-wordcamp-boston-2016.jpg"><img class="wp-image-16384 size-full" src="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/godaddy-wordcamp-boston-2016.jpg" alt="GoDaddy WordCamp Boston 2016" width="640" height="455" srcset="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/godaddy-wordcamp-boston-2016.jpg 640w, https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/godaddy-wordcamp-boston-2016-768x546.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Image: Kari Leigh Marucchi, <a href="http://found-art-photography.com/" target="_blank">Found Art Photography</a></p></div>
<p>We had some very interesting conversations about <a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/smallbusiness/market/pokemon-go-lures-gamers-to-local-businesses-domains/" target="_blank">Pok√©mon Go</a>, accessible technology, augmented reality, exotic candies, <a href="http://www.instructables.com/id/Get-Wound-Up-In-Cats-Cradle/" target="_blank">cat‚Äôs cradle</a>, the chaos of Boston traffic, and (of course) WordPress.</p>
<p><a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/wordcamp-boston.png"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-17092" src="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/wordcamp-boston.png" alt="WordCamp Boston 2016" width="640" height="480" srcset="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/wordcamp-boston.png 975w, https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/wordcamp-boston-768x575.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></a></p>
<p>We weren‚Äôt the only ones playing with the status quo, though. The Automattician duo of Konstantin Obenland and Michael Cain brought their <a href="https://cain.obenland.it" target="_blank">pseudo-morning-television program</a>¬†to Boston in suave style.<em> *cue rockin‚Äô music*</em></p>
<blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-lang="en"><p>
<a href="https://twitter.com/hashtag/wcbos?src=hash">#wcbos</a> <a href="https://twitter.com/hashtag/coitm?src=hash">#coitm</a> Selfie time!! <a href="https://t.co/vVcrvisH8W">pic.twitter.com/vVcrvisH8W</a></p>
<p>‚Äî Konstantin Obenland (@obenland) <a href="https://twitter.com/obenland/status/757243690519846912">July 24, 2016</a>
</p></blockquote>
<p><script src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" async="" charset="utf-8"></script></p>
<p>The pair have been running this setup since <a href="https://2014.phoenix.wordcamp.org/" target="_blank">WordCamp Phoenix in 2014</a>, but it was my first time seeing it unfold in person. It was casual. It was fun.</p>
<p>It was everything that a community event like this <em>should</em> have, and frankly I hope we see more sessions like this at future WordCamps.</p>
<h2>Getting involved means showing up.</h2>
<p><a href="https://twitter.com/melchoyce" target="_blank">Mel Choyce</a>, the special guest on this installment of <em>Cain &amp; Obenland In The Morning</em>, dropped an insightful line: <strong>getting involved is as simple as showing up.</strong></p>
<blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-lang="en">
<p dir="ltr" lang="en">&#8220;Want to get involved? Start showing up.&#8221; &#8211; <a href="https://twitter.com/melchoyce">@melchoyce</a> <a href="https://twitter.com/hashtag/wcbos?src=hash">#wcbos</a> <a href="https://t.co/556saRU8Sh">pic.twitter.com/556saRU8Sh</a></p>
<p>‚Äî Andy McIlwain (@andymci) <a href="https://twitter.com/andymci/status/757244020527624193">July 24, 2016</a></p></blockquote>
<p><script src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" async="" charset="utf-8"></script></p>
<blockquote><p>Showing up. That‚Äôs all you have to do. You don‚Äôt need to speak. You don‚Äôt need to volunteer. You don‚Äôt need to sponsor. You just need to be there.</p></blockquote>
<p>And that‚Äôs what WordCamps and WordPress meetups are for, right? Showing up.</p>
<p>And if you keep showing up, you may get comfortable enough to volunteer.</p>
<p>And once you start volunteering, you might feel comfortable to tell your story through a presentation.</p>
<p>And once you volunteer for a bit you might feel ready to organize a WordCamp, and help other people tell <em>their</em> stories.</p>
<p>You just gotta <a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/webpro/wordpress/how-to-contribute-to-the-wordpress-community/" target="_blank">show up first</a>.</p>
<h2>Where should you show up?</h2>
<p>If you‚Äôre in the Boston area, check out the <a href="http://bostonwp.org/" target="_blank">local WordPress community</a>. They have a <a href="http://www.meetup.com/boston-wordpress-meetup/" target="_blank">meetup group</a>, a <a href="https://twitter.com/bostonwp" target="_blank">Twitter profile</a>, and a <a href="https://www.facebook.com/bostonwp/" target="_blank">Facebook page</a>¬†to keep you in the loop.</p>
<p>If you‚Äôre <em>not</em> in the Boston area, check Meetup.com for a <a href="http://www.meetup.com/topics/wordpress/" target="_blank">WordPress group near you</a>, or the WordCamp Central website for upcoming <a href="http://central.wordcamp.org/" target="_blank">WordCamps in your area</a>.</p>
<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/webpro/wordpress/looking-back-on-wordcamp-boston-2016/">Looking back on WordCamp Boston 2016</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage">Garage</a>.</p>
