e/webpro/wordpress/light-blog-traffic-no-one-visits-site/">Read More</a></p>
<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/webpro/wordpress/light-blog-traffic-no-one-visits-site/">Light blog traffic? Why no one visits your site and what to do about it</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage">Garage</a>.</p>
";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:9:"enclosure";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:3:{s:3:"url";s:82:"https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/blog-traffic-305x170.jpg";s:6:"length";s:1:"0";s:4:"type";s:10:"image/jpeg";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:12:"Ashley Grant";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9353:"<p>Frustrated by light blog traffic? Questioning whether people don‚Äôt like what you have to say, or if your content is not valuable? Pondering why you write the same sort of stuff as other bloggers but don‚Äôt get nearly as many readers to your website?</p>
<p>Not to worry, <a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/webpro/wordpress/lonely-blogger-find-friends-blogosphere/" target="_blank">my bloggy friends</a>! I will explain some of the problems causing your low readership and offer solutions to get your awesomeness exposed, STAT!</p>
<h2>Problem: Nobody knows you exist.</h2>
<p>The sad reality is that building a blog doesn&#8217;t mean you will magically get readers. Think about it ‚Äî how can anyone read your brilliant prose if they don&#8217;t know it&#8217;s out there? When was the last time you stumbled upon a fantastic movie or television show? More often, it comes up in conversation. You hear someone talk about it with excitement, then you go watch it and fall in love with it. Unless you hear about it, you never know to look for it.</p>
<p><a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/blog-traffic-alone.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-15762" src="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/blog-traffic-alone.jpg" alt="Blog Traffic Alone" width="640" height="461" srcset="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/blog-traffic-alone.jpg 640w, https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/blog-traffic-alone-768x553.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></a></p>
<h2>Solution: Promote the heck out of your blog.</h2>
<p>And therein lies your solution. Shout from the rooftops that you have web real estate! Promote your blog on your <a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/smallbusiness/market/using-social-media-to-make-your-blog-more-profitable/" target="_blank">social media channels</a>, tell ALL your friends, and maybe do some <a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/smallbusiness/market/earn-street-cred-by-guest-posting/" target="_blank">guest blogging</a>. Then, once you have gotten the word out to everyone you can, ask others to tell everyone they know.</p>
<div class="callout"> There is no harm in asking for the share. </div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>What is the worst that can happen? Yes, someone can say no, or simply not respond. But if you never ask for the share, the answer will always be no.</p>
<h2>Problem: No one quite gets what your blog is about.</h2>
<p>People like it when you keep it simple. They want to know exactly what they are getting themselves into when they come to your page. If your blog lacks a roadmap, it‚Äôs not only challenging to navigate ‚Äî it‚Äôs hard to figure out what to come back for the next time.</p>
<h2>Solution: Find your niche.</h2>
<p>So, niche it down, baby. Remember, the goal is to attract readers who are interested in something and keep them coming back. Your niche can be a little broad, but don&#8217;t make it <em>too</em> broad. Also, don&#8217;t draw in readers with your niche and jump to a new one without warning.</p>
<p>For example, let&#8217;s say your blog is about horror movies. If you start writing about every type of film except for horror movies, why would a horror-movie buff keep coming back? They will pull a Mike Myers and cut you from their life, man! No one wants to watch their readership die. The horror! The horror!</p>
<div id="attachment_15718" style="width: 650px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/light-blog-traffic.jpg"><img class="wp-image-15718 size-full" src="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/light-blog-traffic.jpg" alt="Light Blog Traffic" width="640" height="605" srcset="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/light-blog-traffic.jpg 640w, https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/light-blog-traffic-768x726.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Photo:¬†<a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/125700716@N07/16456431402/" target="_blank">Q9F</a> via <a href="http://compfight.com">Compfight</a> <a href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/2.0/">cc</a></p></div>
<h2>Problem: You don&#8217;t post often enough.</h2>
<p>Once you do start getting some readers, you have to keep posting quality content to give them an incentive to return. For example, you tell your readers to ‚Äústay tuned for next week‚Äôs discussion of all the ways to prevent foot fungus,‚Äù but you don‚Äôt deliver. How will your readers ever know how to keep the grossness off their toes? They will dump you and move on to another blog that <em>does</em> answer the question. You‚Äôve lost your true love forever.</p>
<h2>Solution: Publish consistently.</h2>
<p>Just as no one likes to get all excited with the first date only to never have a second, don‚Äôt tell your readers to return for a piece on green toenails and refrain from giving them the goods. People like consistency. They want to know that if you tell them new posts will be available every Monday, Wednesday and Friday, new posts are indeed available every Monday, Wednesday and Friday.</p>
<h2>Problem: You post too often.</h2>
<p>As your readership grows, you might need to increase the number of days you post each week. But don&#8217;t go overboard. Let‚Äôs say you have a couponing website with time-sensitive posts. Your readers will expect that you constantly post new information because they know that new coupons come out daily, sometimes hourly. However, there is no reason to post every 20 minutes about hair dye. Not only will you run out of subjects to write about, your audience may feel overwhelmed by too much information.</p>
<h2>Solution: Find the right publishing cadence.</h2>
<p>Keep your readers coming back ‚Äî with genuine interest ‚Äî by spreading out your goodies across several posts. Just because you know everything there is to know about your subject doesn&#8217;t mean you have to post it all at once. Draw it out into sizable chunks, enticing your reading to return again and again.</p>
<p><strong>Pro tip:</strong> Plan a series of related posts. Tease each upcoming article in the preceding post to get readers excited about what‚Äôs in store.</p>
<h2>Problem: Your website is overloaded with ads and pop-ups.</h2>
<p>When I visit a site that is cluttered with ads, I flee. And If I really get into the first paragraph of a post only to be greeted suddenly with a pesky pop-up that will not close, I leave. Oh, how I loathe those websites that make me watch a 30-second ad before getting to what I want to read. Ahem! I&#8217;m talking to you news websites!</p>
<h2>Solution: Find a friendly balance between content and ads.</h2>
<p>Yes, I prefer a site with no fluff, just the news. But I get it ‚Äî you need to monetize. And that‚Äôs fine. Just don‚Äôt lose site of your actual content in all the <a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/webpro/wordpress/blog-spammy/" target="_blank">advertisements and spam</a>. Find a balance that will work for both you and your readers. Besides, there are plenty of other (more meaningful) ways to <a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/smallbusiness/market/5-meaningful-ways-to-make-money-blogging/" target="_blank">make money blogging</a>.</p>
<h2>Problem: Your site takes forever to load.</h2>
<p>You know the type ‚Äî buffering, more buffering, oh, wait! It‚Äôs finally loading! Nope. Still buffering. And now I am bored. I am done with your site. That‚Äôs how quickly a potential reader can abandon your site. Forever.</p>
<h2>Solution: Monitor load times and fix the culprits.</h2>
<p>If this is an issue with your site, <a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/webpro/development/are-slow-website-load-times-costing-you-money-and-pageviews/" target="_blank">read this post</a>. It will walk you through the issues you might need to address, including external APIs, too-large image files and crappy web hosting.</p>
<h2>Get more blog traffic</h2>
<p>I hope this post has provided you with some ideas as to what might be preventing more readers from visiting your site and how you can avoid blog traffic jams. To recap:</p>
<ol>
<li>Avoid a ‚Äúpost it and forget it‚Äù approach to blogging. Promote the heck out of every blog post. <a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/smallbusiness/market/often-promote-blog-posts/" target="_blank">Here are some tips</a> to help with that.</li>
<li>Stick to topics related to the niche you‚Äôve chosen.</li>
<li>Establish a consistent, reasonable publishing schedule.</li>
<li>Limit the amount of advertising content on your site; instead, look for other ways to make money blogging.</li>
<li>Keep close tabs on page load times. Be sure to compress images and host with a reputable company (<a href="https://www.godaddy.com/hosting/web-hosting?isc=cardigan" target="_blank">ahem, GoDaddy</a>).</li>
</ol>
<p>Until next time, fellow bloggers &#8230; May your pageviews and income from blogging reach new heights!</p>
