   			";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:8:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:28:"WP-CLI: command and conquer!";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:71:"https://www.godaddy.com/garage/webpro/wordpress/wp-cli-command-conquer/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:79:"https://www.godaddy.com/garage/webpro/wordpress/wp-cli-command-conquer/#respond";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 15 Jun 2016 14:29:54 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:5:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"WordPress";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"events";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"featured";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"gdauthor";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"wordpress";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:39:"https://www.godaddy.com/garage/?p=15418";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:493:"<p>I use WP-CLI just about every day. It‚Äôs become a central part of my daily life as a WordPress programmer. And it‚Äôs not just useful for... <a class="moretag" href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/webpro/wordpress/wp-cli-command-conquer/">Read More</a></p>
<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/webpro/wordpress/wp-cli-command-conquer/">WP-CLI: command and conquer!</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage">Garage</a>.</p>
";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:9:"enclosure";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:3:{s:3:"url";s:80:"https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/wp-cli-min-305x170.jpg";s:6:"length";s:1:"0";s:4:"type";s:10:"image/jpeg";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:15:"Frankie Jarrett";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:20580:"<p>I use <a href="https://wp-cli.org/" target="_blank">WP-CLI</a> just about every day. It‚Äôs become a central part of my daily life as a WordPress programmer. And it‚Äôs not just useful for managing core, there‚Äôs a growing list of <a href="http://wp-cli.org/docs/tools/" target="_blank">plugins</a> that have WP-CLI commands baked-in, too.</p>
<p>In this article, we won‚Äôt be talking about what WP-CLI is or how to use it ‚Äî we‚Äôve previously covered <a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/webpro/wordpress/how-to-use-wp-cli/" target="_blank">how to use WP-CLI</a>. Instead, we will look at how to <em>create custom WP-CLI commands</em> inside our plugins. That‚Äôs right, it‚Äôs time to get our hands dirty and build something awesome!</p>
<h2>Loading our command</h2>
<p>The developer API for adding custom commands depends on WP-CLI being loaded, so we‚Äôll want to make sure it‚Äôs running when we attempt to register our custom command.</p>
<p>Additionally, if we are in CLI mode then there are likely many additional files in the plugin that don‚Äôt need to be loaded at all (such as admin screens).</p>
<p>When I build a plugin, I often put all of the code for my custom command inside its own file. Then in my main plugin file, I identify the point where everything that my CLI command requires has been loaded, then require my custom command file only when WP-CLI is running and return early to avoid loading anything else.</p>
<h4>Example</h4>
<p><a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Custom-Command-Example.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-15403" src="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Custom-Command-Example.png" alt="WP-CLI Custom Command Example" width="640" height="414" srcset="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Custom-Command-Example.png 640w, https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Custom-Command-Example-768x496.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></a></p>
<p>Let‚Äôs break down the example above:</p>
<ol>
<li>We are always loading the API and Settings classes (presumably our CLI command must need these too).</li>
<li>We are only loading our custom command when the <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">WP_CLI</span> constant is defined, which is a handy way to know we are running WordPress in CLI mode.</li>
<li>We are returning early in the construct, which stops execution and prevents the <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">class-admin.php</span>¬†file from loading. We are in CLI mode after all, so there‚Äôs no need to load anything related to the admin area.</li>
</ol>
<h2>Registering our command</h2>
<p>Now that we have properly loaded our command, let‚Äôs open up <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">class-cli.php</span>¬†and start working with the WP-CLI developer API to register our command.</p>
<p>It‚Äôs as easy as creating a class, and using <a href="http://wp-cli.org/docs/internal-api/wp-cli-add-command/" target="_blank"><span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">WP_CLI::add_command()</span></a> to register it.</p>
<h4>Example</h4>
<p><a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Register-Command-Example.png"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-15412 size-full" src="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Register-Command-Example.png" alt="Register Command Example" width="640" height="377" srcset="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Register-Command-Example.png 640w, https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Register-Command-Example-768x452.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></a></p>
<p>Let‚Äôs break down the example above:</p>
<ol>
<li>We are registering a custom command called <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">my-plugin</span>¬†using <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">WP_CLI::add_command</span>¬†on the last line.</li>
<li>The custom command points to the <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">My_Plugin_Command</span>¬†class.</li>
<li>Since <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">greet()</span>¬†is a public method, a sub-command called <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">greet</span>¬†is automatically registered.</li>
<li>Since <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">get_year()</span>¬†is a private method, we can only call it inside our class.</li>
</ol>
<p>Alright, let‚Äôs try it out in the terminal:</p>
<p><a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Register-Command-Terminal.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-15413" src="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Register-Command-Terminal.png" alt="WP-CLI Register Command Terminal" width="640" height="60" srcset="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Register-Command-Terminal.png 640w, https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Register-Command-Terminal-768x72.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></a></p>
<p>We just wrote a custom command. Pretty cool!</p>
<p><strong>Pro tip:</strong> It‚Äôs important to register a command that is <em>unique</em> to your plugin or project. Think of it as the namespace that all of your sub-commands will live under.</p>
<h2>Understanding args</h2>
<p>WP-CLI command methods accept two types of arguments: <strong>positional</strong> and <strong>associative</strong>.</p>
<p>Let‚Äôs go a little deeper with our <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">greet</span>¬†sub-command, and allow the user to control who the greeting is for using <strong>positional</strong> arguments.</p>
<h4>Example</h4>
<p><a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Positional-Arg-Example.png"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-15410 size-full" src="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Positional-Arg-Example.png" alt="WP-CLI Positional Arg Example" width="640" height="172" srcset="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Positional-Arg-Example.png 640w, https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Positional-Arg-Example-768x206.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></a></p>
<p>Let‚Äôs break down the example above:</p>
<ol>
<li>Positional arguments are passed in the <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">$args</span>¬†array.</li>
<li>Each argument can be accessed using its numeric index, starting with zero.</li>
</ol>
<p>Alright, let‚Äôs try it out in the terminal:</p>
<p><a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Positional-Arg-Terminal.png"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-15411 size-full" src="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Positional-Arg-Terminal.png" alt="WP-CLI Positional Arg Terminal" width="640" height="60" srcset="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Positional-Arg-Terminal.png 640w, https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Positional-Arg-Terminal-768x72.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></a></p>
<p>Let‚Äôs say we want displaying the year to be optional. After all, most people already know what year it is. We can easily do this using an <strong>associative</strong> argument.</p>
<h4>Example</h4>
<p><a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Associative-Arg-Example.png"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-15401 size-full" src="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Associative-Arg-Example.png" alt="WP-CLI Associative Arg Example" width="640" height="215" srcset="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Associative-Arg-Example.png 640w, https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Associative-Arg-Example-768x258.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></a></p>
<p>Let‚Äôs break down the example above:</p>
<ol>
<li>Associative arguments are passed in the <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">$args_assoc</span>¬†array.</li>
<li>Each argument can be accessed via its associative index (e.g. <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">show-year</span>).</li>
<li>If we see <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">show-year</span>¬†in the index, we will display the year after the greeting.</li>
</ol>
<p>Alright, let‚Äôs try it out in the terminal:</p>
<p><a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Associative-Arg-Terminal.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-15402" src="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Associative-Arg-Terminal.png" alt="WP-CLI Associative Arg Terminal" width="640" height="117" srcset="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Associative-Arg-Terminal.png 640w, https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Associative-Arg-Terminal-768x140.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></a></p>
<p>Great. Everything works. But there is something about our code that is kind of messy. Can you tell? That <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">isset()</span>¬†check just seems like it could be cleaner. Luckily, in WP-CLI there is a way to easily clean things up!</p>
<p>Introducing <a href="http://wp-cli.org/docs/internal-api/wp-cli-utils-get-flag-value/" target="_blank"><span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">WP_CLI\Utils\get_flag_value()</span></a></p>
<h4><strong>Example</strong></h4>
<p><a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Get-Flag-Example.png"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-15406 size-full" src="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Get-Flag-Example.png" alt="WP-CLI Get Flag Example" width="640" height="304" srcset="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Get-Flag-Example.png 640w, https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Get-Flag-Example-768x364.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></a></p>
<p>Let‚Äôs break down the example above:</p>
<ol>
<li>The <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">get_flag_value()¬†</span>method helps us easily grab a value from the associative index.</li>
<li>In the example above, we don‚Äôt need the value, we only need to check if it exists.</li>
<li>If the index does not exist, the default value will be <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">null</span>.</li>
<li>We can optionally pass a third parameter to set the default to be anything we want.</li>
<li>This is a clean and handy alternative to doing <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">isset()</span>¬†checks everywhere.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Bonus:</strong> By using <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">get_flag_value()</span>¬†we also have automatic support for <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">&#8211;no-show-year</span>. This is a feature built-in to WP-CLI that allows a boolean option flag to be negated.</p>
<h2>Using PHPDoc</h2>
<p>Now the real magic begins. You might think that <a href="https://www.phpdoc.org/" target="_blank">PHPDoc</a>¬†blocks are nothing more than a developer best-practice. Well in WP-CLI, they aren‚Äôt just a nice-to-have description of our methods, they are actually a functional part of our command!</p>
<p>Let me explain‚Ä¶</p>
<p>In our examples above, you may have noticed we did a big ‚Äúno-no‚Äù in PHP. We didn‚Äôt use <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">isset()</span>¬†to check if the numeric indexes existed before trying to reference them. We are printing <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">$args[0]</span>¬†and <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">$args[1]</span> without any checks whatsoever. What were we thinking?! We all know what this will lead to: Undefined Index notices. Super. Annoying.</p>
<p>Well, this is where PHPDoc in WP-CLI actually saves the day (and a bunch of lines of code).</p>
<h4>Example</h4>
<p><a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-PHPDoc-Example.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-15408" src="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-PHPDoc-Example.png" alt="WP-CLI PHPDoc Example" width="640" height="380" srcset="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-PHPDoc-Example.png 640w, https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-PHPDoc-Example-768x456.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></a></p>
<p>Let‚Äôs break down the example above:</p>
<ol>
<li>By using WP-CLI‚Äôs magic PHPDoc syntax, we can make sure certain arguments are required.</li>
<li>The <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">first-name</span>¬†and <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">last-name</span>¬†arguments will always be required.</li>
<li>The <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">&#8211;show-year</span>¬†associative argument flag will be optional.</li>
<li>If our users are having trouble remembering how to use the command, they can simply use the global <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">&#8211;help</span>¬†flag to display this PHPDoc in their terminal!</li>
</ol>
<p>Alright, let‚Äôs try it out in the terminal:</p>
<p><a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-PHPDoc-Terminal.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-15409" src="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-PHPDoc-Terminal.png" alt="WP-CLI PHPDoc Terminal" width="640" height="114" srcset="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-PHPDoc-Terminal.png 640w, https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-PHPDoc-Terminal-768x136.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></a></p>
<h2>Output: Strings</h2>
<p>The truth is, the usefulness of our custom commands relies a lot on how we output them. Thankfully, WP-CLI has once again done all of the heavy lifting for us, we just have to properly use the output methods available to us.</p>
<p>The most common type of output in commands are going to be the strings we print to the terminal.</p>
<p>The greeting message in our example above can be displayed a number of different ways using WP-CLI helper methods, each one tailored to a different context.</p>
<h4>Example</h4>
<p><a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Output-Strings-Example.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-15407" src="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Output-Strings-Example.png" alt="WP-CLI Output Strings Example" width="640" height="459" srcset="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Output-Strings-Example.png 640w, https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Output-Strings-Example-768x550.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></a></p>
<h2>Output: Global options</h2>
<p>When considering the output of our command, it‚Äôs also important to be familiar with the <a href="https://wp-cli.org/config/" target="_blank">global options</a>¬†that are built-in to WP-CLI.</p>
<p>As you can see in the previous string examples, some methods behave differently depending on what global options might be in use.</p>
<p>For instance, if a user runs a command using the <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">&#8211;quiet</span>¬†global option, all output messages will be suppressed <em>except</em> when using <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">WP_CLI::line()</span>. It stands to reason that this method should be used sparingly as it will <em>always</em> be printed to the terminal. We should use <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">WP_CLI::log()</span>¬†instead.</p>
<p>Imagine the frustration of a user trying to use the <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">&#8211;quiet</span>¬†flag only to see dozens of lines appear! Let‚Äôs be developers who pay attention to those kinds of UX details in our output. It‚Äôs important, even in the terminal.</p>
<h2>Formatting arrays</h2>
<p>There will be times when we want to display an array of information to our user, and give them options to display it the way they want. Never fear, <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">WP-CLI::format_items()</span>¬†is here!</p>
<p>Let‚Äôs say that we have a list of different types of greetings in our plugin, and we want the user to be able to list them all the terminal.</p>
<h4>Example</h4>
<p><a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Format-Arrays-Example.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-15404" src="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Format-Arrays-Example.png" alt="WP-CLI Format Arrays Example" width="640" height="452" srcset="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Format-Arrays-Example.png 640w, https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Format-Arrays-Example-768x542.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></a></p>
<p>Let‚Äôs break down the example above:</p>
<ol>
<li>Our greetings are stored in an array of arrays called <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">$items</span>.</li>
<li>Each greeting has a <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">type</span>¬†and a <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">text</span>¬†key.</li>
<li>We are using the <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">get_flag_value()</span>¬†method to get the <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">&#8211;format</span>¬†option value.</li>
<li>If <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">&#8211;format</span>¬†is not specified, we will display a table by default.</li>
<li>We pass our <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">$format</span>, <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">$items</span>, and key names to the <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">WP_CLI::format_items()</span>¬†method.</li>
</ol>
<p>Alright, let‚Äôs try it out in the terminal:</p>
<p><a href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Format-Arrays-Terminal.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-15405" src="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Format-Arrays-Terminal.png" alt="WP-CLI Format Arrays Terminal" width="640" height="413" srcset="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Format-Arrays-Terminal.png 640w, https://www.godaddy.com/garage/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/WP-CLI-Format-Arrays-Terminal-768x495.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></a></p>
<p>Nice!</p>
<p>With just a few lines a code we‚Äôve given our users the ability to not only view an array of data, but easily format it the way they want using a <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">&#8211;format</span>¬†option.</p>
<p>The <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">WP_CLI::format_items()</span>¬†method accepts <strong>table</strong>,<strong> json</strong>,<strong> csv</strong>,<strong> yaml</strong>,<strong> ids</strong>, and <strong>count</strong> as valid format types, which we can describe in the PHPDoc for this new <span style="font-family: 'Courier New';">greetings</span>¬†sub-command.</p>
<h2>Conclusion</h2>
<p>As you can see, there are a ton of useful tools in the WP-CLI developer API. This is great news for us developers as we look to level-up our plugins, and provide our advanced users with powerful ways to use them in the terminal.</p>
<p>I would be remiss to not point you to the official WP-CLI developer resources at this point. They contain all of the technical information about helper methods, the arguments available in them, and many great examples.</p>
<ul>
<ul>Commands Cookbook:</ul>
</ul>
<p><a href="http://wp-cli.org/docs/commands-cookbook/" target="_blank">http://wp-cli.org/docs/commands-cookbook/</a></p>
<ul>
<ul>Internal API:</ul>
</ul>
<p><a href="http://wp-cli.org/docs/internal-api/" target="_blank">http://wp-cli.org/docs/internal-api/</a></p>
<p>In this article we‚Äôve only scratched the surface of what we can do with custom commands. Was it helpful for you? Did you end up writing a custom command for your plugin? Let me know in the comments, or <a href="https://www.godaddy.com/community/Developer-Portal/Adding-WP-CLI-commands-to-your-WordPress-plugins/m-p/3329#M154">join the discussion in the community</a>.</p>
<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage/webpro/wordpress/wp-cli-command-conquer/">WP-CLI: command and conquer!</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://www.godaddy.com/garage">Garage</a>.</p>
